<br>
Kingpin has a huge head to body ratio when in comparison to most heroic bodied comic characters.  He's not short by any means though.<br>
<br>
Another &quot;fat effect&quot; is posture.  Don't forget that when the weight on a person is distributed differently it tends to effect the way that they move, sit and stand.<br>
<br>
When drawing comics everything is exagerated.  Especially when drawing the posture of muscular characters, especially men.  Notice how they always stand with their feet far apart, their shoulders back and the chest is usually puffed up.  You'll want to keep the exageration but reverse the effect.  Make them look like they're slouching a little.<br>
<br>
Women tend to have a more sultry posture.  Hips and shoulders are cocked.  Breasts are usually drawn like the woman is puffing up her chest (even when she isn't).  To make a woman appear fat draw her breasts a bit less perkier than the typical heroine.  And if she's REALLY obese make them sag a little.<br>
<br>
In manga most characters are very slim.  Not that any aren't muscular but the overall trait is to have skinny characters.  When drawing a typically fat character in manga don't overdo it.  Don't draw them morbidly obese unless that's the effect you're seeking.  What you should do is make them a bit chubby or husky.<br>
<br>
Most people tend to overlook this point almost entirely.  Don't make the same mistake.<br>
<br>
Well I hope I've helped you out. <p><BR><BR>Aw Crap.<BR><BR>
